			<h4><a id="comment_link_64195960" name="comment_link_64195960" href="//tech.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23207468&amp;cid=64195960" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64195960)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64195960" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64195960); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~ctilsie242">ctilsie242</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~ctilsie242">( 4841247 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64195960"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64195960"><p>There was a time with Macs, in the System 7-9 range, where a cooperative-tasking OS was definitely not up to snuff.  It was a standard operating procedure to restart when doing a work session, restart afterwards, and restart every few hours, because if one application misses their WaitNextEvent() call, the OS was hung, and you have to reach for the interrupt or reset button.  Comp.sys.mac.advocacy discussed this to no end in the early 1990s, and how WorkPlaceOS or even A/UX was going to save the platform.<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64195960">

