</li></ul></li></ul></li></ul></li><li id="tree_64193630" class="comment full contain"><span class="ind"></span>
<div id="comment_status_64193630" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64193630" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64193630" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64193630" name="comment_link_64193630" href="//tech.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23207468&amp;cid=64193630" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64193630)" >Microsoft&rsquo;s&rdquo;cheating&rdquo; wasn&rsquo</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64193630" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64193630); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>5</a>, Informative)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~Yaztromo">Yaztromo</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~Yaztromo">( 655250 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64193630">		
		on Saturday January 27, 2024 @10:56PM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//tech.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23207468&amp;cid=64193630">#64193630</a>)
		<small><a href="http://web.me.com/yaztromo" title="http://web.me.com/yaztromo" class="user_homepage_display">Homepage</a>
<a href="//slashdot.org/~Yaztromo/journal/" title="Wednesday May 20, 2009 @03:30PM" class="user_journal_display">Journal</a> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64193630"><p>it was about beating OS/2.</p><p>Most of the other UNIX&rsquo;s weren&rsquo;t designed to run on 80x86 platforms, so they were never in any real contention with Microsoft.  AIX, HPUX, Solaris, Dynix (which was Intel based but had a special architecture separate from PCs) &mdash; none of these were in the same market as Windows.</p><p>No, Microsoft&rsquo;s target was OS/2 &mdash; which had a bigger resource footprint, but was also a vastly superior OS, with real pre-emptive multitasking, a (by 90&rsquo;s standards) modern high performance file system, the ability to pre-emptively multitask Windows 3.x and DOS apps well before Windows 95, and a superiors desktop environment (a modern Workplace Shell would still absolutely slay).  It was here that Microsoft introduced Win32s and kept changing it every few weeks to break OS/2 compatibility for newer Windows apps.  It was here that the per-processor agreements were put into place with systems manufacturers to make selling OS/2 on systems more expensive (for those too young to know, in these agreements the manufacturer paid and charged for a Windows license with every system sold &mdash; even if it didn&rsquo;t come with Windows.  So if you wanted an OS/2 system you were paying for both OS/2 and a Windows license you didn&rsquo;t actually get).</p><p>UNIX wasn&rsquo;t even on Microsoft&rsquo;s radar in the 90&rsquo;s &mdash; it just wasn&rsquo;t a PC operating system, and was mostly targeted to systems that didn&rsquo;t compete with Microsoft.  If you wanted a UNIX system, you had to buy your hardware from your OS vendor (much like with macOS today) &mdash; virtually nobody (except some of the early cool kids running Linux and *BSD) was buying white-box Intel systems and running UNIX &mdash; the numbers were too small for Microsoft to care.  OS/2 was their real target &mdash; and in the end, it worked.</p><p>Yaz</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64193630">
<span class="ind"></span><a id="reply_link_64193630" class="btn link" href="//tech.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23207468&amp;op=Reply&amp;threshold=1&amp;commentsort=0&amp;mode=thread&amp;pid=64193630" onclick="D2.replyTo(64193630); return false;">Reply to This</a> 	<a href="#" class="comment_share_toggle btn link">Share</a>
	<div class="comment_share sharethis-0 hide"><span class="au"></span>
